You can use `le_or_le_of_add_le_add h0.ge` here

I don't think this lemma is worth having:
1. We almost never have lemmas taking an equality as an assumption. The reasons are that
  a. The user is (almost) always able to substitute that equality before trying to apply any lemma
  b. Adding all possible such lemmas would lead to combinatorial explosion
2. Once you substitute `M` in, the proof is structurally made of existing lemmas, namely `(mem_erase_of_ne hyp.symm).2 (mem_cons_self ..)`

```suggestion
@[simp] theorem sub_singleton [DecidableEq α] (a : α) (s : Multiset α) : s - {a} = s.erase a := by
```

```suggestion
theorem mem_sub [DecidableEq α] : a ∈ s - t ↔ t.count a < s.count a := by
  rw [← count_pos, count_sub, Nat.sub_pos_iff_lt]
```
then your original lemma can be obtained using `count_pos` again and `count_eq_zero_of_not_mem`

Indeed, (also as a side note to myself ;-)) the original lemma can be proved as follows:

`
theorem mem_sub_of_not_mem_of_mem {α} [DecidableEq α] (x : α) (X Y: Multiset α) (x_in_X : x ∈ X)
    (x_notin_Y : x ∉ Y) : x ∈ X - Y := by
  rwa [mem_sub, count_eq_zero_of_not_mem, count_pos]
  assumption
`

```suggestion
theorem inter_add_sub_of_eq [DecidableEq α] {M N P Q : Multiset α} (h : M + N = P + Q) :
```

Can you put a few more brackets so that it's clear whether it's supposed to be read as
```suggestion
    N = N ∩ (Q + (P - M)) := by
```
or
```suggestion
    N = (N ∩ Q) + (P - M) := by
```

Given that this works, I think we don't need this lemma
```suggestion
  rw [← H, sub_singleton, erase_cons_head]
```

This is a cool lemma. I thought I could reduce it to some silly statement but actually I can't
```suggestion
theorem inter_add_sub_of_add_eq_add [DecidableEq α] {M N P Q : Multiset α} (h : M + N = P + Q) :
    (N ∩ Q) + (P - M) = N := by
```

For readability
```suggestion
theorem mem_sub [DecidableEq α] {a : α} {s t : Multiset α} :
    a ∈ s - t ↔ t.count a < s.count a := by
```
`simp only ...`?
I think `split` should be considered a fancy tactic here
What does "fancy" mean here? That we do not need to change this to `simp only`?
Yes, basically. See eg https://leanprover.zulipchat.com/#narrow/stream/113488-general/topic/Terminal.20tidy/near/293210921
I disagree here, I've seen plenty on nonterminal simps before a split break.
I pushed a change for this. Also turns out that `erase_singleton` is not used here.
